	abstract = {The German Ideology, an essay on Marx's philosophy of history was originally written by Marx and Engels in 1845-46, but not published until 1932. Marx argues that the real basis of history had been previously neglected and sets out to formulate a materialist conception of history opposed to the “high-sounding dramas of princes and states” (163). The first premise of real history, he argues, is the existence of “human individuals” in relation to one another and nature (149). Men must be in a “position to live in order to ‘make history'” (155-156). Moreover, for Marx, the human individual is never isolated. To live is to be embedded in social relations, most fundamentally the reproduction of the family. Although the family is the basis for social relations, Marx argues, “civil society is the true source and theatre of all history” (163). Each generation lives within a realm simultaneously new and unchanged. This is to say that while the historical circumstances are specific and continuously modified, these modifications are driven by the articulation of productive forces and social relations (172). To write materialist history, therefore, one must begin with the study of this articulation over time. Marx's effort to articulate a materialist conception of history in The German Ideology is a undergirded by a pointed critique of German idealist philosophy and historiography. He argues that idealistic views of history understand every period through the lens of a category, reversing the causal relationship between the idea and material practice: "Conceiving, thinking, the mental intercourse of men, appear at this stage as the direct efflux of their material behaviour. The same applies to mental production as expressed in the language of politics, laws, morality, religion, metaphysics, etc., of a people. Men are the producers of their conceptions, ideas, etc. – real active men, as they are conditioned by the definite development of their productive forces and of the intercourse corresponding to these, up to its furthest forms" (154). Ideology – morality, religion, philosophy – are, for Marx, never independent of “real-life” (i.e. material) processes. “They have no history, no development{\textbackslash}ldotsLife is not determined by consciousness, but consciousness by life” (155). So where does the dominant ideology of a given period come from? Marx argues, “the ideas of the ruling class are in every epoch the ruling ideas{\textbackslash}ldotsthe ideas of its dominance” (172). He conceptualizes ideology as the byproduct of class struggle, a medium in which the ruling class – that is, the class which controls the material forces of society – represents its interest as the general interest (161). This observation was, of course, extended by Gramsci (2003) who argued that the role of intellectuals of the dominant class was to work within society in order to produce “spontaneous consent” by the dominated classes. Labor in the ruling class is divided into mental and material forms. The role of mental labor by professionalized “conceptual ideologists” is to work on the illusion of the ruling class about itself, representing its ideas as universal (173-174). Language and consciousness, like ideology, are represented as epiphenomena for Marx in this essay. Language arises “only from need” and consciousness is concerned, at first, only with “the immediate sensuous environment” and “limited connection with other persons and things” (158). It is only through the division of labor, Marx argues, that consciousness can first be imagined as existing independent of material connections (159).},
